{"cursor":"23058","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n\n\n'Recruitment' refers to the process of attracting, screening, selecting, and\nonboarding a qualified person for a job. At the strategic level it may involve\nthe development of an employer brand which includes an 'employee offering'.\n\nThe stages of the recruitment process include: job analysis and developing a\nperson specification; the sourcing of candidates by networking, advertising, or\nother search methods; matching candidates to job requirements and screening\nindividuals using testing (skills or personality assessment); assessment of\ncandidates' motivations and their fit with organisational requirements by\ninterviewing and other assessment techniques. The recruitment process also\nincludes the making and finalising of job offers and the induction and\nonboarding of new employees. [http://www.acas.org.uk/index.aspx?articleid=748 The recruitment\nprocess \"Acas\"], Accessed 5 August 2012\n\nDepending on the size and culture of the organisation recruitment may be\nundertaken in-house by managers, human resource generalists and / or recruitment\nspecialists. Alternatively parts of all of the process might be undertaken by\neither public sector employment agencies, or commercial recruitment agencies, or\nspecialist search consultancies.\n","linknr":552,"url":"Lateral_hiring","recorded":1362579793,"links":39,"instances":["personnel","role"],"pdf":[],"categories":["Recruitment|","Employment","Human resource management","Human resource management associations"],"headings":["Recruitment process","Recruitment approaches","Talent Acquisition","See also","Recruiting Companies","References"],"image":["//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/9/99/Question_book-new.svg/50px-Question_book-new.svg.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/f/f2/Edit-clear.svg/40px-Edit-clear.svg.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/a5/ArmyCareersOxford20051022_CopyrightKaihsuTai.jpg/220px-A